Sure! Here's an example of how you can make a beetle animation in CSS:

```
/* Define the beetle image as a background image */
.beetle {
  background-image: url('https://i.imgur.com/mrHRrHi.png');
  background-repeat: no-repeat;
  background-size: contain;
  width: 50px;
  height: 50px;
  position: absolute;
  top: 50%;
  left: 50%;
  transform: translate(-50%, -50%);
  animation: beetle-run 2s linear infinite;
}

/* Define the beetle animation */
@keyframes beetle-run {
  0% { transform: translate(-50%, -50%) rotate(0deg); }
  50% { transform: translate(-50%, -50%) rotate(10deg); }
  100% { transform: translate(-50%, -50%) rotate(0deg); }
}
```

To use this code, add a `<div>` element with the class `beetle` inside the `.background` element. The beetle image will move in a running motion around the page.

Note: You will need to have an image of a beetle or provide a link to a beetle image to use this code. Replace the `url` value with the URL of your image.

